Thanh, Tho, Tieu, Vinh, Anh, Beo, Binh, Chau.","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surnames 麥 (see   Mai   2) and 莫 (see   Mo   1).","Vietnamese (<b>Mạc</b>): from Chinese 莫 ‘nothing; nonexistent’; see   Mo   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Mai","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Vietnamese Hung, Thanh, Hoa, Son, Dung, Long, Binh, Minh, Thu, Hue, Huong, Thuy.  Chinese Chi, Hong, Ho, Sang, Han, Hang, Jian, Li, Man, Mei, Sen, Wei.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 麥, meaning ‘wheat’ in Chinese: (i) from Mai Qiu (麥丘), the title of a man in the state of Qi (located mainly in present-day Shandong province) during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ), who, despite being very old, came to celebrate the birthday of the Duke Huan of Qi (ruler of the state of Qi, died 643  BC ). His descendants inherited 麥, the first part of his title, as their surname. (ii) borne by descendants of Mai Tie Zhang (麥鐵杖), a famous general during the Sui dynasty (581–618  AD ). His descendants were scattered around southern China.","Chinese: Mandarin and Cantonese form of the surname 買, meaning ‘buy’ in Chinese: (i) borne by descendants of the king Song Weizi, founder of the state of Song. (ii) borne by descendants of the Duke Dao of Xu (ruler of the state of Xu, 546–523  BC ), possibly inheriting his personal name. (iii) from the first element of the personal name Mai Zhu Chu (買朱鉏), style name of an official who lived during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). (iv) it has also been traced back to other ethnic groups in northern China."]}]},{"name":"Carthy","type":"LAST","meanings":["Car, dear, and tir, a country, and ać for neać, an individual, originally cartać, meaning a beloved countryman","Irish: A beloved countryman"],"variants":[]},{"name":"Sadhbh","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional name, pronounced ‘syve’, from an obsolete Irish word meaning ‘sweet’. In Irish legend, Sadhbh, daughter of Conn Cétchathach (Conn of the Hundred Battles), was considered ‘the best woman in Ireland who ever lay with a man’. It was a common girl's name during the Middle Ages and has been revived in modern times. It has been Anglicized as <b>Sabina</b> and <b>Sally</b>."],"variants":[{"name":"Sive","meanings":["Anglicized form of   Sadhbh ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Sadhbh Mac Carthy was born about 1255, in Ireland as the daughter of Philip kennedy. She married Toirdhealbhach Mór Ó Briain, King of Thomond in Mor, Chuuk, Micronesia. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. She died in Ennis, County Clare, Ireland, and was buried in Ennis, County Clare, Ireland."},"et":{"about 1255–":"umbes 1255–Surnud","1255–Female":"1255–Surnud","1245–1306":"1245–1306","1265–1329":"1265–1329","1290–1311":"1290–1311","–1311":"–1311","1230–Male":"1230–Surnud","abt. 1290":"umbes 1290","ABT 1265":"umbes 1265","1311":"1311","1245":"1245","1255":"1255","1265":"1265","1230":"1230","about 1255":"umbes 1255","1329":"1329","1290":"1290","1306":"1306","Thomond, North Munster, Clare, Ireland":"Thomond, County Clare, Iirimaa","Ennis, Clare, Munster, Ireland":"Ennis, County Clare, Iirimaa","Ireland":"Iirimaa","Killaloe, Clare, Ireland":"Killaloe, County Clare, Iirimaa","First wife of Turlogh Mor":"Mor, Chuuk, Mikroneesia"},"fi":{"about 1255–":"noin 1255–Kuollut","1255–Female":"1255–Kuollut","1245–1306":"1245–1306","1265–1329":"1265–1329","1290–1311":"1290–1311","–1311":"–1311","1230–Male":"1230–Kuollut","abt. 1290":"noin 1290","ABT 1265":"noin 1265","1311":"1311","1245":"1245","1255":"1255","1265":"1265","1230":"1230","about 1255":"noin 1255","1329":"1329","1290":"1290","1306":"1306","Thomond, North Munster, Clare, Ireland":"Thomond, County Clare, Irlanti","Ennis, Clare, Munster, Ireland":"Ennis, County Clare, Irlanti","Ireland":"Irlanti","Killaloe, Clare, Ireland":"Killaloe, County Clare, Irlanti","First wife of Turlogh Mor":"Mor, Chuuk, Mikronesia"},"fr":{"about 1255–":"environ 1255